    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-04-29T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-04-29T18:00:00-05:00" n="19"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d19">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851<gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>.00/4–2849:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Consulate General at Saigon</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d19fn1">Repeated by the Department as 1384 to Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-04-29T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 29, 1949—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>69. <gloss target="#t_urtel1">Urtel</gloss> 129, Apr 28.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d19fn2">Not printed.</note> You shld indicate to DuGardier<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d19fn3">Diplomatic counselor to the French High Commissioner
                        in Indochina.</note> U.S. Govt has no intention recognizing Chi Commie
                    regime precipitously, and that in any case Chi Commies have not organized
                    themselves into govt to be recognized; that we see no objection for time being
                    trade Commie-controlled areas China through private channels so long as
                    commodities of strategic importance Sov area not involved; that U.S. considering
                    application export controls China for purpose prohibiting or restricting
                    strategic items primarily with view prevent their re-export <pb facs="0035"
                        n="21" xml:id="pg_21"/> via China to USSR, eastern Europe and northern
                    Korea. For <gloss target="#t_urinfo1">urinfo</gloss>, matter recognition has
                    been discussed Brit and Fr Embs here. Our position vis-à-vis trade has been
                    discussed Brit and intend take up with Fr Emb shortly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
